            <label key="d4926d89778b9e8d318c9e4a21bae6b5">
                <text>PET Scans</text>
            </label>
            <label key="752c558079842855c69f71c3cf0841fc">
                <text>A Positron Emission Tomography (PET) scan is a medical imaging test used to diagnose and monitor some diseases.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="7fd7999a2cd31f2523a369e50055d0e8">
                <text>Before the PET scan, the doctor injects a small amount of a ’radiotracer’ solution into the patient’s body. Diseased cells absorb more of the solution than normal cells.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="04472a1beff578e1250b1f3b7e4c4741">
                <text>The radiotracer contains radioisotope atoms that decay (break down). As they decay, the radioisotope atoms release pairs of gamma rays. Simultaneously, each gamma ray travels in a straight line in the opposite direction to the other ray. The ring scanner detects the gamma rays that strike it.</text>
            </label>
            <label key="0f00d7e8b721860ec8f371bd16a303fd">
                <text>Radioisotopes each have a ‘half-life’. Half-life can be described in the two following ways:</text>
            </label>
            <label key="440681bb35f0c3158e16c1502268a82a">
                <text>time required for one-half of the radioactive atoms in a sample to decay</text>
            </label>
            <label key="97914eeae098eb9ffa56b410c7f03384">
                <text>time required for the number of radioactive atoms that decay per second in a sample to decrease by one-half (50%).</text>
            </label>
            <label key="8d56bf504198b53dfa3915dc01f5d0ef">
                <text>
                    <strong>‌Examples of radioisotopes‌</strong>
                </text>
            </label>
